commentBody:
@Shrike 

The point is: Neither usage is "more correct".

That's true for tamale, panini, and all the others as well.

@Brooke Husic, PHD
Care to share the alternative with the class? 
And the emus, if they're still around.

@Barry Ancona 
He's probably too busy getting ready for Thanksgiving dinner with the fam.

(Oh God, don't tell *they're* gonna be here, too!)

@Barry Ancona - Thanks for the call-out! 

I had a busy day today and, although I usually get to the puzzles in the morning, alas, it took me until now (7PM in the evening, to be redundant) to get to them. 

It seems whenever I'm later than usual getting to the puzzles, there is a CLAM-related entry!

@Shrike 
Agreed. I have a portable hard drive, and it would fit in my pocket, but I'd never call it a POCKET HARD DRIVE.

(I've now read the word "pocket" so many times that it doesn't sound like a word anymore. Pocket pocket pocket.)

@Katie 

“(I've now read the word ‘pocket’ so many times that it doesn't sound like a word anymore. Pocket pocket pocket.)”

It’s really weird when that happens, isn’t it?

@Grumpy 

Oddly enough, I went to a family reunion this summer. My sister showed up with her husband and four children. 

Her family was the largest group there.

@sotto voce 

On my iPad and iPhone, the i flashes only when the note is something you really need to see to be able to make sense of the puzzle. 

I don’t know now whether there used to be a circle around it or if I am misremembering.

@sotto voce
The i does not flash on Android.  I usually chime after an apple user posts about the flash, but didn't today.
I have developed the habit of checking under the Android i everyday to see the constructor's name, and of course on Sundays the title, and that has saved me on the occasions where there is also a Note.

@Vaer 

That's a great idea. I'll just start making it a habit to click the "i" first thing, no matter what.

Thanks!

@sotto voce 

Thanks! It is gorgeous here today, so we walked a few miles and saw another house we looked at but didn’t buy. (We went in a different direction on Monday’s walk, and went past two other houses we looked at when house-hunting.)

Hope you’re having a great day, too.

@Steven 

Yeah, if you went into Best Buy in 1995 and asked for a "pocket hard drive" they would probably laugh, and then take you to the Iomega section. There were portable hard drives, but they weren't something you would put in your pocket - well maybe some geeks would. 

Isn't the best meaning of PhD, "piled higher and deeper"? :D

@Justin 

Thanks for that link. Interesting reading. 

For anyone who (like me) is unfamiliar with the National Health Law Program (NHeLP), it’s an NGO whose “mission  . . .  is to protect and advance the health and civil rights of low-income and undeserved individuals and families in the United States.”

@Steve L 
You may be interested (and amused?) to know that master bedroom is now seen as "problematic" by that PC-journal "House Beautiful".  The more acceptable term is becoming "main bedroom".

<a href="https://www.housebeautiful.com/lifestyle/fun-at-home/a1087/master-bedroom-politically-incorrect" target="_blank">https://www.housebeautiful.com/lifestyle/fun-at-home/a1087/master-bedroom-politically-incorrect</a>/

@Bill in Yokohama 

Brooke Husic is one of my favorite contemporary constructors, though the puzzles she they puts on her website (they put on their website?) often have many cultural references that are far outside my experience. 

The Tuesday New Yorker puzzle was a nice challenge that took me almost twice as long as this one. It also took me longer than any New Yorker puzzle in the past few months.

@Eric Hougland 
I really liked it.  It was the 500th Connections, so maybe Wyna wanted it to be extra fun. 
Also, in my Android app a Connections Archive has appeared today.

@MFSTEVE 

You've come to the right place.

A sizeable number of varieties are represented here.

@MFSTEVE 
Me, too.  We were the Mathletes!
(A less athletic group would be hard to find.)

@Nancy, Grant and Seward

I never got to DEDUCE because I was being a wise guy and on the first pass through the acrosses I put in DATE for 38A.

Once of the many nice misdirects in this puzzle.  Really liked this one.

@Nancy 

I fell into the same two traps.

Nicely stated.  In keeping with the theme, I should say that was a PHantasticDissertation.

@RozzieGrandma 

If I could, I would share a picture of my sister-in-law, who’ll be 75 in December, throwing axes at a bar in Dallas. She and her partner are the only people who I know to have done that. 

I first read about it in the NYT five or six years ago (which probably means eight or nine years ago). The combination of alcohol and axes has always struck me as unwise.

@Times Rita 

Maybe you should take another look at the clue. It was [Nothing runs like a ___]. 

(My wife’s car certainly was able to stop a deer. Unfortunately, it also stopped the car, and we got it back a few thousand dollars later from the auto body shop. Thankfully, most of that was State Farm’s money.)

@Barry
I was reading your response as 

...is also short for... NASDAQ

@Red Carpet 

It doesn’t bother me because I have already solved Connections, but some people might not appreciate the spoilers. 

There *is* a forum for Connections: <a href="https://www.nytimes.com/2024/10/22/crosswords/connections-companion-500.html" target="_blank">https://www.nytimes.com/2024/10/22/crosswords/connections-companion-500.html</a>

@Bonnie 

Nice to see you back!

Im guilty as charged when it comes to Strands, but I would point out that there is no official Strands forum.
